{"id": "11466", "revid": "49243392", "url": "https://darksouls.fandom.com/wiki?curid=11466", "title": "Baby Skeleton", "text": "Baby Skeletons are in \"&lt;a href=\"Dark%20Souls\"&gt;Dark Souls&lt;/a&gt;\".\nLocation.\nBaby Skeletons are located in the &lt;a href=\"Tomb%20of%20the%20Giants\"&gt;Tomb of the Giants&lt;/a&gt;, in the area with &lt;a href=\"Pinwheel%20Servant\"&gt;Pinwheel Servant&lt;/a&gt;s, that leads to &lt;a href=\"Gravelord%20Nito\"&gt;Gravelord Nito&lt;/a&gt;'s Tomb.\nGeneral Information.\nBaby Skeletons cause &lt;a href=\"Negative%20Status%20Effects%23Toxic\"&gt;Toxic&lt;/a&gt; build-up and tend to attack in groups. Unlike most enemies, Baby Skeletons can infinitely respawn out of the flooded ground, regardless of whether the player has rested at a &lt;a href=\"Bonfire%20%28Dark%20Souls%29\"&gt;bonfire&lt;/a&gt; or not. Given their high &lt;a href=\"Humanity%20%28Item%29\"&gt;humanity&lt;/a&gt; drop rate, this trait makes them good candidates for farming humanity. Furthermore, their AI combined with their small size and slow speed causes them to run into walls and group up, making farming easy. However, their drops usually vanish extremely quickly, making it paramount to pick them up immediately after killing them. They only seem to spawn while the player is inside the water or very close to it, right next to him."}
{"id": "7608", "revid": "27795815", "url": "https://darksouls.fandom.com/wiki?curid=7608", "title": "Backstab", "text": "Backstabs are a form of &lt;a href=\"critical%20attack\"&gt;critical attack&lt;/a&gt; and &lt;a href=\"gameplay%20mechanic\"&gt;gameplay mechanic&lt;/a&gt; in \"&lt;a href=\"Dark%20Souls\"&gt;Dark Souls&lt;/a&gt;,\" \"&lt;a href=\"Dark%20Souls%20II\"&gt;Dark Souls II&lt;/a&gt;,\" and \"&lt;a href=\"Dark%20Souls%20III\"&gt;Dark Souls III&lt;/a&gt;\".\nGeneral information.\nPlayers may perform a backstab if they position themselves behind a humanoid enemy and do a light attack with shield down. Enemies must be on roughly the same level surface as the player. Backstabs can be performed with nearly every type of weapon, although exceptions exist (see &lt;a href=\"%23Weapons\"&gt;below&lt;/a&gt;).\nBackstabs deal high damage based on the damage of the weapon and its critical rate.\nBackstabs cannot be interrupted. While in the motion of backstabbing, both the perpetrator and the victim are granted invincibility frames and cannot take further damage except for damage-over-time effects such as being &lt;a href=\"poison\"&gt;poison&lt;/a&gt;ed, under the effects of &lt;a href=\"toxic\"&gt;toxic&lt;/a&gt;, or while using &lt;a href=\"Power%20Within\"&gt;Power Within&lt;/a&gt;. An exception to invincibility frames is \"Dark Souls II\", where you can still take damage during a backstab although the damage is reduced. \nMost humanoid enemies can be backstabbed. Most enemies that can be &lt;a href=\"Parry%20and%20Riposte\"&gt;parried and riposted&lt;/a&gt; can also be backstabbed. Some non-humanoid enemies, such as the &lt;a href=\"Fang%20Boar\"&gt;Fang Boar&lt;/a&gt; in the &lt;a href=\"Undead%20Parish\"&gt;Undead Parish&lt;/a&gt; (but not the ones in &lt;a href=\"Anor%20Londo\"&gt;Anor Londo&lt;/a&gt;), can also be backstabbed, but generally non-humanoid enemies are impossible to backstab.\nIt is possible for two players or monsters to backstab a single target at once (each dealing their standard backstab damage). This requires precise timing and positioning, however.\nDifference between games.\nThe difference is very slight although most players report that backstabbing seems harder in \"Dark Souls II\". It feels that the 'backstab window' is a bit narrow in the second game. Also for safer backstabbing in \"Dark Souls\" it's usually better to move a little bit towards the enemy's right shoulder, and in \"Dark Souls II\" towards their left shoulder. \"Dark Souls III\" seems to nearly mirror \"Dark Souls\". \nIt is far easier to backstab in the first game as you can be backstabbed even while rolling and in the second game you may roll away to avoid it.\nEnemies.\nWhen an page displays information on backstabbing (\"Backstab\", under \"Characteristics\"), this refers to whether or not the enemy can be backstabbed.\nInformation on whether the enemy can perform backstabs will be listed under \"Abilities\" and are also displayed here:\nWeapons.\nThe following is a list of &lt;a href=\"Weapons%20%28Dark%20Souls%29\"&gt;weapons&lt;/a&gt; that \"cannot\" backstab."}
{"id": "177936", "revid": "36018463", "url": "https://darksouls.fandom.com/wiki?curid=177936", "title": "Backstep", "text": ""}
{"id": "10946", "revid": "356896", "url": "https://darksouls.fandom.com/wiki?curid=10946", "title": "Balder", "text": "Balder is a mentioned &lt;a href=\"location\"&gt;location&lt;/a&gt; in \"&lt;a href=\"Dark%20Souls\"&gt;Dark Souls&lt;/a&gt;\".\nLore.\n&lt;a href=\"Dark%20Souls\"&gt;Dark Souls&lt;/a&gt;.\nBalder was an ancient kingdom of humans. It was the homeland of &lt;a href=\"Knight%20King%20Rendal\"&gt;Rendal&lt;/a&gt;, the legendary Knight King who wore a &lt;a href=\"Ring%20of%20Steel%20Protection\"&gt;ring&lt;/a&gt; capable of granting its wearer with the protection of iron, increasing the defense against physical attacks, thus leading many legends to circulate about him, as it was said that not even the claws of a gigantic wyvern would be able to damage it. Rendal was so important that &lt;a href=\"Silver%20Coin\"&gt;Silver Coin&lt;/a&gt; were minted with his portrait on its face, similar to the faces of the gods &lt;a href=\"Allfather%20Lloyd\"&gt;Lloyd&lt;/a&gt; and &lt;a href=\"McLoyf\"&gt;McLoyf&lt;/a&gt;, although these coins of great value in the world of men had little value in Lordran. &lt;a href=\"Balder%20Knight\"&gt;Balder Knight&lt;/a&gt;s wore &lt;a href=\"Balder%20Set\"&gt;armor made from thick iron plates&lt;/a&gt; and used &lt;a href=\"Balder%20Shield\"&gt;shields&lt;/a&gt; tweaked for improved stability and &lt;a href=\"Balder%20Side%20Sword\"&gt;rock-solid, long sword&lt;/a&gt; that were excellent for thrusting attacks.\nHowever, with the fading of the &lt;a href=\"First%20Flame\"&gt;First Flame&lt;/a&gt;, more and more &lt;a href=\"Undead\"&gt;Undead&lt;/a&gt; started to appear among humans, to the point that in Balder it reached a widespread outbreak and the kingdom was reduced to ruins in the ensuing chaos. Knight King Rendal thus gathered the remaining knights of his country and left for &lt;a href=\"Lordran\"&gt;Lordran&lt;/a&gt;, the ancient kingdom of the gods where according to legend the Undead would have to pilgrimage and overcome various tests to learn about their fate. In an attempt to reach &lt;a href=\"Anor%20Londo\"&gt;Anor Londo&lt;/a&gt; to link the fading Flame and thus save what remained of their kingdom, nullifying the Curse of Undeath, Rendal and his knights arrived at the &lt;a href=\"Sen%27s%20Fortress\"&gt;Sen's Fortress&lt;/a&gt; which tested the potential Chosen Undead with deadly challenges. However, even if they were able to navigate the fortress, Sendal and his knights never managed to overcome the final test of the &lt;a href=\"Iron%20Golem\"&gt;Iron Golem&lt;/a&gt; placed to defend the entrance to the city of the gods from countless heroes trying to reach it, and continued to try and fail for decades until even the Knight King himself died, losing his ring in the fortress, leaving the now hollowed knights to wander around aimlessly.\n&lt;a href=\"Dark%20Souls%20II\"&gt;Dark Souls II&lt;/a&gt;.\nIn the times and region of &lt;a href=\"Drangleic\"&gt;Drangleic&lt;/a&gt;, despite Rendal's failure, his &lt;a href=\"Ring%20of%20Steel%20Protection%20%28Dark%20Souls%20II%29\"&gt;ring&lt;/a&gt; that offered great physical protection was passed around but his tales became long forgotten and even the greatly wizened had no recollection of his exploits, thus remaining the last trace of Balder's existence.\n&lt;a href=\"Dark%20Souls%20III\"&gt;Dark Souls III&lt;/a&gt;.\nIn the times and region of &lt;a href=\"Lothric\"&gt;Lothric&lt;/a&gt;, despite the many centuries that passed, Rendal's &lt;a href=\"Ring%20of%20Steel%20Protection%20%28Dark%20Souls%20III%29\"&gt;ring&lt;/a&gt; that offered great physical protection was passed around and it was said that he was lined with steel on the inside, such that even the talons of mighty dragons did him little harm, thus keeping the last trace of Balder's existence until the last days of the Fire."}
